.TH "socklog\-check" "8" 
.SH NAME
socklog\-check \- checks for the availability of a socklog(8) service.
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]socklog\-check\f[R] [\-v] [unix [\f[I]address\f[R]]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]socklog\-check\f[R] attempts to connect to a \f[B]socklog\f[R](8)
unix service and reports whether the connection attempt succeeded or
not.
.PP
It connects to the datagram oriented unix domain socket
\f[I]address\f[R], and reports success through the return code.
If \f[I]address\f[R] is not specified, \f[B]socklog\-check\f[R] attempts
to connect to \f[I]/dev/log\f[R].
.PP
When running services that use the syslog facility under runit\[aq]s
service supervision, \f[B]socklog\-check\f[R] should be added to the top
of the service\[aq]s run script to ensure that no syslog messages are
generated until a syslog service is up and running to process the
messages, e.g.:
.IP
.EX
#!/bin/sh
socklog\-check || exit 1
exec service_using_syslog
.EE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
verbose.
Print verbose message to standard error.
.SH EXIT CODES
On success \f[B]socklog\-check\f[R] returns 0.
.PP
On error, \f[B]socklog\-check\f[R] prints a message to standard error
and exits 111.
